Airut are bipedal, boar-like creatures who follow the goddess Tuska. Before Tuska's demise, they lived on her back, riding and controlling her with massive reins. They are also found on Mazcab where they are typically found wandering desert areas. They were named after an ancient warrior of the same name by the Naragi when Naragun was attacked by the airut and Tuska. They drop the level 90 melee power gloves, razorback gauntlets, as well as pieces of the Tuska mask and pages of Kaigi's journal. They are also a very good source of Crimson Charms. Airut require 92 Slayer to harm.

They have a special attack that is signalled when they roar and hit their chest. The airut's damage will be doubled, in addition to a faster attack speed (2x for ranged, 4x for melee) while it is in a "frenzy" state. If the airut is successfully hit with Flurry or Rapid Fire, when they signal this attack or are in the process of using it, they will be disoriented. While disoriented, the airut is stunned and takes double damage from all attacks; this also stacks with damage boosting abilities like Berserk.

They also have two passive abilities that increase their armour the lower their health is. One gives them +5 armour for every 0.4% of health missing, and the other gives them 5 defence levels for every 10% of health they have lost to direct damage from the player (damage from reflects does not count towards this).

The airut on Mazcab may be poisoned with Nemi poison to turn them into Sickly airut. The sickly airut are easier to kill, which may be useful when needing to kill some for a reputation task from Trinks, but they do not provide a number of other benefits of killing airut, such as drops or Slayer experience.

Airut came to Gielinor via portals, signalling Tuska's upcoming arrival.

Update history[edit | edit source]

This information has been compiled as part of the update history project. Some updates may not be included – see here for how to help out!
  • patch 4 May 2020 (Update):
    • Runite stone spirits have been replaced by drakolith and banite stone spirits.
  • patch 17 September 2018 (Update):
    • A typo when asking Morvran about tips on fighting Airut as your slayer task has now been corrected.
  • patch 23 July 2018 (Update):
    • A certain sand tile near the airut no longer hides noted drops.
  • patch 22 January 2018 (Update):
    • All sand tiles near the airut area now render correctly.
  • patch 6 February 2017 (Update):
    • Fixed an issue where airut were only spawning as melee-variants on Mazcab.
  • patch 23 November 2015 (Update):
    • Airut on Mazcab no longer give the 'Another player is already fighting this Airut' message when there is nobody fighting them.
  • ninja 9 June 2014 (Update):
    • The drop rate of sirenic scales from airut and dark beasts has been reduced.
  • patch 7 January 2014 (Update):
    • The airut death animation no longer flickers when the creature is meant to disappear.
  • update 3 December 2013 (Update):
    • Added to game.

Trivia[edit | edit source]

  • In Finnish, the word 'airut' means 'harbinger'.
  • Despite their examine text, they are not aggressive, although they are aggressive when encountered in Raids.
  • Initially, airut did not have their own unique Slayer icon; they shared the same Slayer icon as the Scutarius - this was later fixed.
  • Airut, along with Cadarn rangers, are the only non-magic using monsters to drop sirenic scales.
  • Previously, when asking Kuradal or Morvran for advice on these creatures, they would say that they are weak to stab despite them having no explicit weakness. A similar issue occurred with Kal'gerion demons. This was corrected in a hidden update, and they now state that they have no weakness.
  • Razorback gauntlets were originally dropped regardless of whether you were on a Slayer assignment, but this was updated on 14 April 2014.
  • When Mazcab was released, there was a bug where the airut there would only spawn in melee stance; they could still switch to their ranged stance if idle. This was changed a year after its release as airut in the other locations spawn in both melee and ranged stances.
  • As of 1 February 2018, the highest kill count for this monster was 288,093 kills.[3]
    • This had not increased by 6 May 2018.[4]
